WEBVTT

00:02.000 --> 00:05.680
A vacancy has appeared
and you're going to fill it.

00:06.000 --> 00:08.920
From now on, Mr Shelby,
you shut your gypsy mouth

00:09.000 --> 00:10.920
and listen to your instructions.

00:11.160 --> 00:14.760
CAMPBELL: <i>I know it was you who carried
out the murder of Mr Duggan.</i>

00:15.000 --> 00:19.640
-(GUNSHOT)
-You are on my hook, Mr Shelby.

00:20.360 --> 00:22.800
-Name?
-Harold Hancox.

00:22.880 --> 00:25.000
-Have you ever been arrested?
-No.

00:25.080 --> 00:26.920
TOMMY: Arthur, we can stand him up.

00:27.440 --> 00:30.240
<i>Last night, one of our men had
his throat cut in Winston Green.</i>

00:30.320 --> 00:31.840
I'm not real!

00:31.920 --> 00:35.960
Gentlemen? This is your cousin.
Polly's son, Michael.

00:36.040 --> 00:38.520
-I want to go with them.
-Over my dead body.

00:38.600 --> 00:40.920
Do we hear 800 guineas? 850.

00:41.000 --> 00:43.720
MAY: <i>May Car let on.
I breed race horses and train them.</i>

00:43.800 --> 00:46.480
-So will you consider me?
-I will consider you.

00:46.760 --> 00:48.320
Thomas Shelby?

00:48.400 --> 00:50.320
(GUNSHOT)

00:51.920 --> 00:53.520
POLLY: <i>Did they behave themselves?</i>

00:53.800 --> 00:56.160
They were really amazing.

02:20.760 --> 02:24.080
(CHURCH BELLS RING)

02:46.760 --> 02:50.200
You might think this is a curious
place for me to suggest a meeting,

02:50.840 --> 02:52.800
but...

02:52.880 --> 02:55.480
your surprises have only just begun.

03:05.880 --> 03:08.680
You look a little unsteady, Mr Shelby.

03:09.400 --> 03:11.040
Take a seat.

03:17.520 --> 03:18.760
You're working together.

03:20.360 --> 03:23.000
Blowing up the Garrison was your idea.

03:24.240 --> 03:26.000
You chose me.

03:29.920 --> 03:33.000
It's funny, I thought the
Fenians had a policy...

03:33.080 --> 03:34.800
-Enough.
-Eh? Of not mixing

03:34.960 --> 03:36.080
the personal with the political.

03:36.160 --> 03:37.360
-I said enough.
-I think

03:37.440 --> 03:39.000
I will decide on what is enough.

03:39.080 --> 03:41.640
Who's in charge here then, eh?
Who's in charge?

03:41.920 --> 03:44.240
Right, let me understand this.

03:44.320 --> 03:47.080
-You answer to an agent of the Crown.
-CAMPBELL: Perhaps we can just...

03:47.160 --> 03:50.040
-Very interesting.
-Perhaps we can stick to the agenda.

03:50.120 --> 03:52.560
-Whose agenda?
-There is a form of words here.

03:52.640 --> 03:54.520
-Whose words?
-Arrogant bastard.

03:56.120 --> 03:57.960
I'm not accustomed
to being spoken to like that.

03:58.080 --> 03:59.200
CAMPBELL: Just come to order.

03:59.280 --> 04:01.560
I am here to listen,
but not to the fucking infantry.

04:01.640 --> 04:03.880
Enough! Jesus!

04:03.960 --> 04:05.400
Now...

04:07.520 --> 04:11.160
Some weeks ago, Mr Shelby
carried out a military mission

04:11.240 --> 04:15.120
on behalf of pro-treaty Republicans
here in Birmingham.

04:15.200 --> 04:16.440
You...

04:16.520 --> 04:18.320
Working for the King.

04:18.400 --> 04:21.720
-There is a unique political situation.
-Yeah? How does that feel?

04:22.280 --> 04:24.320
-Let us...
-Tell me. How does that fucking feel?

04:24.400 --> 04:25.680
...stick to the form of words.

04:25.760 --> 04:28.080
-Temporarily, we have a shared interest.
-Oh, I see.

04:28.160 --> 04:30.320
-Shall we just stop him laughing?
-You want me to stop laughing?

04:31.560 --> 04:32.880
Explain this, pal.

04:33.080 --> 04:35.200
Following the success of your mission...

04:35.320 --> 04:37.760
-We're going to make you do it again.
-Will you shut up?

04:37.840 --> 04:40.200
Can we just conduct
ourselves here, please?

04:40.280 --> 04:41.800
-Conduct ourselves!
-Please.

04:41.880 --> 04:45.520
No one in this room wants to breathe
the same air as anyone else.

04:48.280 --> 04:50.960
-Nevertheless...
-Nevertheless the pro-treaty Paddies

04:51.040 --> 04:53.080
and the King want the same man dead.

04:54.880 --> 04:56.440
Am I right?

05:18.800 --> 05:21.600
-Why him?
-Did you ask why in France?

05:22.520 --> 05:26.880
-Yeah.
-So, it's the same answer, because.

05:33.840 --> 05:35.240
Why me?

05:36.200 --> 05:38.520
-Because.
-Because.

05:41.560 --> 05:43.280
Because if anybody connects me to this,

05:43.400 --> 05:45.840
it will be assumed
that it was a criminal act

05:45.960 --> 05:47.760
and not a political one.

05:47.840 --> 05:51.440
No, you need not fear being
connected to the killing

05:51.520 --> 05:54.880
because I will see to it that
no connection is ever made.

05:55.440 --> 05:58.360
You will have complete
immunity after the fact.

05:58.920 --> 06:02.760
But, in the execution, you will get
no help from agents of the Crown.

06:03.200 --> 06:04.560
And we can't be seen to be involved.

06:06.760 --> 06:09.720
You have been chosen, Mr Shelby,

06:10.240 --> 06:11.800
and there really is no choice.

06:12.080 --> 06:14.360
No equals bang,

06:14.440 --> 06:17.200
and your man here will shed no tears
as he looks the other way.

06:23.160 --> 06:24.720
Nevertheless...

06:25.520 --> 06:26.800
I say no.

06:33.400 --> 06:35.600
CAMPBELL: Mr Shelby?

06:41.000 --> 06:44.200
What about your export licence,
Mr Shelby?

06:44.280 --> 06:46.720
You had a deal with Mr Churchill.

06:52.240 --> 06:55.240
The one with the mouth,
Donal Henry, he is a spy.

06:55.640 --> 06:58.200
He is working for the Irregulars
against the pro-treaty Paddies.

06:58.320 --> 07:00.520
He reports every fucking
word back to them.

07:00.600 --> 07:01.800
No, it's not possible.

07:01.880 --> 07:04.640
They've both been security vetted
by my own department.

07:04.720 --> 07:07.080
I have men in places your men can't go.

07:07.200 --> 07:10.040
Donal Henry meets the
anti-treaty Paddies in the back room

07:10.160 --> 07:13.520
of the Mother Red Cap in Saltley,
sometimes twice a week.

07:14.800 --> 07:17.440
These Irish enemies are
fucking brothers and cousins.

07:17.520 --> 07:20.360
You are stepping into a world
you don't understand.

07:24.000 --> 07:27.840
If what you're saying is true,
he'll be dealt with.

07:27.920 --> 07:32.480
Bring me proof the spy is dead
and we have a deal.

07:49.440 --> 07:50.600
Mr Shelby.

07:50.800 --> 07:52.400
-Billy boy.
-Watch it.

08:00.280 --> 08:02.160
Now on you go.

08:54.720 --> 08:57.720
Right, boys, let's go!

09:00.360 --> 09:03.400
(SCREAMING)

09:11.160 --> 09:13.840
(BOTTLE SMASHES)

09:31.320 --> 09:33.160
Fuck you!

09:33.240 --> 09:35.080
Mario!

09:36.360 --> 09:38.160
Mario!

09:42.280 --> 09:44.160
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

09:45.320 --> 09:47.680
Mario!

09:47.760 --> 09:49.480
Come here.

09:53.600 --> 09:56.200
Sabini's day is done.

09:57.880 --> 09:59.560
I'll protect you now.

10:02.120 --> 10:03.720
Oh, shut up!

10:04.120 --> 10:06.360
Stop fucking whingeing.

10:08.120 --> 10:11.400
Due to my razor blade,

10:11.480 --> 10:14.560
and a few complaints from the neighbours

10:14.640 --> 10:17.440
about the terrible fucking music...

10:22.520 --> 10:25.720
Do you want to tell them or should I?

10:25.800 --> 10:29.360
This place is under new management.

10:35.040 --> 10:38.080
<i>By order of the Peaky Blinders.</i>

10:48.320 --> 10:50.400
(WOMEN GIGGLE)

10:53.080 --> 10:55.920
(LAUGHING)

11:32.280 --> 11:33.280
(SIGHING)

11:38.560 --> 11:40.760
(CLEARING THROAT)

12:23.800 --> 12:25.320
-(CLEARS THROAT)
-(KNOCKING)

12:25.680 --> 12:27.040
TOMMY: Yes?

12:28.400 --> 12:29.960
Somebody to see you, Mr Shelby.

12:30.040 --> 12:31.880
He says he's come about the
position of accounts clerk.

12:32.960 --> 12:34.640
Send him in.

12:37.760 --> 12:40.480
-WOMAN: Just through here, sir.
-MICHAEL: Thank you.

12:44.520 --> 12:45.960
Michael...

12:48.160 --> 12:49.760
Vacancy's been filled.

12:52.560 --> 12:54.640
Not according to this morning's paper.

13:03.120 --> 13:05.120
At school, I was top of the
class in mathematics,

13:05.240 --> 13:08.200
and I did a night school course in
accountancy at Worcester College.

13:10.960 --> 13:12.560
Mum says you've had
six different accountant clerks

13:12.640 --> 13:13.960
in the last six months.

13:16.200 --> 13:20.000
When respectable men see the
other things you do, they leave.

13:21.760 --> 13:25.200
But I, like Lizzie out there,
already know what you do.

13:27.920 --> 13:31.200
Mum says you want to be 80% legal
within two years.

13:31.280 --> 13:33.520
-Three.
-I can help.

13:35.160 --> 13:38.760
I know both sides and
you know you can trust me.

13:40.080 --> 13:44.440
I want to help you, Tommy, become legal.

13:46.400 --> 13:48.280
Do the right thing.

13:52.240 --> 13:53.800
I want to be proud of this family.

14:01.560 --> 14:03.120
Does Polly know you're here, Michael?

14:05.440 --> 14:07.200
I'm 18 on Friday, I go where I please.

14:23.720 --> 14:25.400
You phone your mother.

14:28.400 --> 14:30.000
Good luck.

14:36.840 --> 14:38.680
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

14:38.760 --> 14:41.120
We're not open for winnings yet.

14:41.320 --> 14:43.120
MAY: I'm here to see Thomas Shelby.

14:48.120 --> 14:50.240
I have an appointment.

14:50.320 --> 14:51.960
Come in.

15:05.040 --> 15:07.520
-May Car let on.
-Mr Shelby has his proper meetings

15:07.600 --> 15:09.560
in his other office.

15:11.040 --> 15:13.840
This was the address that he gave me.

15:13.920 --> 15:16.600
-He gave you this address?
-He said it was a gambling den.

15:17.800 --> 15:19.560
I told him that I'd wanted to see one

15:19.640 --> 15:21.360
since I'm always reading
about them in the papers.

15:22.000 --> 15:24.840
Quite the big scandal
in <i>The Telegraph</i> lately.

15:24.920 --> 15:27.880
Anyway, he said that
I could come and have a look.

15:30.960 --> 15:32.360
And now I feel like a bit of an idiot

15:32.440 --> 15:34.560
because I'm early and he's late
and I have no idea how to behave.

15:35.160 --> 15:36.520
In a gambling den?

15:39.000 --> 15:41.520
I'll wait in the car.

15:41.600 --> 15:44.080
If I open the door again,
they'll all want to come in.

15:45.520 --> 15:47.200
Like flies.

15:51.880 --> 15:53.000
So what are you?

15:54.080 --> 15:55.800
(STAMMERING) What am I?

15:55.880 --> 15:57.360
To Thomas?

15:59.000 --> 16:02.440
I'm going to train his racehorse...
For Epsom.

16:03.560 --> 16:05.000
You know horses?

16:06.320 --> 16:08.880
Yes. You?

16:08.960 --> 16:10.240
Born riding.

16:11.640 --> 16:14.400
I slept in a manger when I was a baby.

16:16.080 --> 16:17.880
I was born riding, too.

16:18.200 --> 16:20.160
(DOOR OPENS)

16:21.640 --> 16:24.280
JOHN: There's a fucking
great Riley parked out there

16:24.360 --> 16:25.640
and nobody's watching it.

16:25.720 --> 16:29.800
John, this woman says
she's training Thomas' horse.

16:33.240 --> 16:34.960
He's told us a lot about you.

16:37.160 --> 16:38.640
Don't know where he is, do you?

16:38.720 --> 16:40.680
(DOOR OPENS)

16:42.720 --> 16:45.160
Sorry I'm late.
There was a family matter.

16:45.240 --> 16:47.040
Esme, keep it locked up for a minute.

16:47.160 --> 16:49.760
-Yes, Thomas.
-I'll show you around.

16:57.880 --> 17:00.920
So, be my guest.

17:11.120 --> 17:13.200
That's my brother Arthur's office.

17:17.760 --> 17:19.720
Down there is my brother John's office,

17:19.800 --> 17:22.400
that's where we slate
the runners and the riders.

17:25.560 --> 17:28.360
It's so out in the open.
What about the police?

17:29.680 --> 17:31.160
What about them?

17:33.360 --> 17:36.440
When I drove into Small Heath,
I thought I was going to get murdered...

17:36.680 --> 17:38.680
Then I mentioned your name.

17:40.200 --> 17:42.320
It was like being escorted
to see a king.

17:45.680 --> 17:48.360
-You came here to get my girl, right?
-Right.

18:04.040 --> 18:05.520
She looks in very good condition,

18:05.600 --> 18:07.920
considering she's not been
out on the gallops.

18:08.120 --> 18:10.000
Curly's the best horseman in England.

18:10.080 --> 18:12.640
I have a man called Mickey
who'd argue the point.

18:12.720 --> 18:15.200
Ah, Curly here is half horse himself.

18:15.280 --> 18:17.440
She's blessed. Very blessed.

18:17.520 --> 18:19.400
Well, she's from the best stock.

18:19.920 --> 18:21.920
But I'd rather have a coloured pony.
Mixed blood is stronger.

18:22.640 --> 18:24.200
Not to win the Derby, Curly.

18:24.280 --> 18:26.320
Don't like them racing, Tommy,
not the way they beat them.

18:26.800 --> 18:29.520
-She's all yours.
-Thank you.

18:33.120 --> 18:34.840
TOMMY: He gets sad when one leaves.

18:35.560 --> 18:38.840
-What time is your box van coming?
-Midday.

18:38.920 --> 18:41.800
Maybe you've got time to take
the lady to the Garrison,

18:41.880 --> 18:43.680
show her the spa and the tearooms.

18:46.080 --> 18:48.000
I'd like that, why not?

18:54.520 --> 18:58.040
TOMMY: I just had it done up.
There was a fire.

18:58.120 --> 18:59.640
It's...

18:59.720 --> 19:02.160
Yeah.

19:02.240 --> 19:03.720
What do you drink?

19:04.960 --> 19:06.720
So early, but gin.

19:23.560 --> 19:25.120
Goodness. With something?

19:27.920 --> 19:29.520
Like what?

19:30.960 --> 19:32.480
Tonic water or...

19:34.200 --> 19:37.560
Erm... We have, erm...

19:37.720 --> 19:39.000
Cordial.

19:40.560 --> 19:42.080
There's not much room in there but...

19:53.560 --> 19:55.400
You want to fuck me, Mrs Car let on?

19:58.160 --> 19:59.880
Perhaps because I...

20:00.400 --> 20:03.080
Perhaps because I would represent
something to you?

20:05.120 --> 20:07.480
We should have this conversation
before the booze

20:08.360 --> 20:10.000
starts talking for us.

20:13.160 --> 20:14.560
You have a horse.

20:16.720 --> 20:18.600
Yes, I have a horse.

20:19.240 --> 20:21.720
The horse is why I'm here.

20:23.040 --> 20:24.400
Purely that.

20:25.160 --> 20:28.200
And because you're paying me a
lot of money to train your horse,

20:28.280 --> 20:29.760
that's why I'm here.

20:30.360 --> 20:31.640
Purely that.

20:35.680 --> 20:37.280
Good.

20:38.320 --> 20:40.160
Good. Well, a toast, then.

20:40.960 --> 20:42.840
To the horse, to the Derby.

20:47.080 --> 20:48.800
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

20:53.880 --> 20:56.040
So is that what you say to women?

20:59.240 --> 21:00.920
Only if I don't know what they want.

21:01.720 --> 21:03.760
And what if they don't want to fuck?

21:05.240 --> 21:07.320
Then life is simpler.

21:07.400 --> 21:08.960
You want a simple life?

21:13.000 --> 21:15.760
Do I look like a man
who wants a simple life, eh?

21:17.120 --> 21:18.560
So what do you want?

21:21.000 --> 21:23.720
For what I'm paying you, Mrs Car let on,

21:23.920 --> 21:27.840
I want a horse that'll pay out
at Epsom on an each-way bet.

21:33.720 --> 21:36.680
Before I took your account,

21:37.200 --> 21:38.640
I did some credit checks on you.

21:40.680 --> 21:43.360
Apparently, you don't exist.

21:48.840 --> 21:50.840
My existence is questionable.

21:53.520 --> 21:55.440
Gypsies don't like registers.

21:56.800 --> 22:00.720
You see, I'm not gypsy like you mean.

22:00.800 --> 22:02.720
But you did register for France.

22:04.680 --> 22:06.680
I also sent your name to the War Office,

22:07.280 --> 22:09.520
I have friends there.

22:09.600 --> 22:11.840
You won two medals for gallantry.

22:14.120 --> 22:17.320
Does that really impress you,
Mrs Car let on?

22:21.760 --> 22:23.200
Call me May.

22:30.200 --> 22:32.120
Charlie says the box van's here.

22:33.320 --> 22:34.880
Thank you, Finn.

22:38.080 --> 22:40.200
You know, I still don't know what
you're going to call your horse.

22:43.200 --> 22:46.280
The horse will be called Grace's Secret.

22:48.960 --> 22:50.560
Grace's Secret.

22:56.720 --> 22:59.600
I told him he definitely
can't take the job.

23:01.160 --> 23:03.760
He said, "All right,
I'll move to London, then."

23:03.840 --> 23:07.680
I said, "I won't give in to blackmail.
No is no."

23:09.160 --> 23:12.400
Well... That settles it, then.

23:13.520 --> 23:16.280
I'll give the job
to the other candidate.

23:16.360 --> 23:18.320
He's much better qualified anyway.

23:18.400 --> 23:22.160
Michael did City and Guilds, six months.

23:22.240 --> 23:24.400
Yeah, but he doesn't know racing, Poll.

23:25.280 --> 23:28.400
He knows horses,
but he doesn't know racing.

23:28.800 --> 23:30.960
This other boy, he knows racing.

23:31.040 --> 23:32.920
He's good. He's a fast learner.

23:36.280 --> 23:38.360
What if Michael really leaves?

23:39.720 --> 23:41.880
You just got to let him go, Poll.

23:41.960 --> 23:44.600
He'll get a job in an office in London.

23:44.680 --> 23:46.160
I'm sure he'll write to you.

23:47.160 --> 23:48.720
He made a big speech

23:48.800 --> 23:53.160
about wanting to help you
build up a respectable business.

23:53.240 --> 23:55.000
Oh, he's like his dad,
he could make me cry.

23:55.480 --> 23:57.040
There are trains to London.

23:58.400 --> 23:59.880
So I just let him leave?

24:00.400 --> 24:02.280
Every month or so he'd be back.

24:03.600 --> 24:05.520
Unless, of course, he meets a girl.

24:05.880 --> 24:07.720
Then, who knows?

24:13.080 --> 24:14.880
Oh, my God.

24:16.360 --> 24:18.000
You want him to do this job.

24:18.080 --> 24:21.080
Polly, I want what you want.

24:22.760 --> 24:26.160
What about this other more
qualified candidate?

24:26.880 --> 24:29.000
Mmm...

24:29.080 --> 24:30.680
Well, I lied, there isn't one.

24:35.640 --> 24:37.240
How much you paying?

24:38.760 --> 24:40.880
-The advertised rate.
-Like hell.

24:41.680 --> 24:43.640
-Three bob.
-Like hell.

24:44.720 --> 24:46.440
-Three and six.
-Four.

24:47.840 --> 24:49.360
Four it is.

24:55.000 --> 24:56.880
-I love him, Tom.
-I know.

24:57.520 --> 25:00.640
That's why I'll keep him away
from the old business,

25:00.720 --> 25:03.120
put him charge of the new. Agreed?

25:04.280 --> 25:05.840
Agreed.

25:15.240 --> 25:17.920
Well, Finn, you've got two choices,
mild or mild.

25:18.600 --> 25:21.080
-Mild.
-There you go.

25:21.160 --> 25:23.680
-(DOOR OPENS)
-Here he is, look.

25:25.480 --> 25:27.720
(CHEERING)

25:27.800 --> 25:29.400
Happy birthday, Michael.

25:29.520 --> 25:32.400
Eighteen years old. You're a man today.

25:32.480 --> 25:33.760
Give him a drink, John boy.

25:33.880 --> 25:35.160
-There you go, lad.
-And after that,

25:35.600 --> 25:37.680
we'll go to find you
a lady of the night.

25:37.760 --> 25:38.960
Arthur!

25:42.800 --> 25:44.760
TOMMY: Michael. (CLEARS THROAT)

25:44.840 --> 25:46.440
What's that?

25:46.760 --> 25:48.720
TOMMY: So you're never late for work.

25:53.120 --> 25:55.400
ARTHUR: Welcome to the business,
Michael.

25:55.480 --> 25:58.720
-Welcome to the business.
-Thank you.

25:58.800 --> 26:00.880
Right, come on, let's get him drunk.
Come here, you.

26:00.960 --> 26:02.160
All right, whisky.

26:02.240 --> 26:06.320
No whisky, he's at work tomorrow.
Give him only dark mild.

26:06.400 --> 26:07.440
A toast.

26:07.800 --> 26:09.280
-ARTHUR: Toast.
-To Michael.

26:09.360 --> 26:10.960
ALL: To Michael.

26:22.720 --> 26:24.840
(DOOR OPENS)

26:28.200 --> 26:29.840
You all right?

26:38.360 --> 26:40.880
-What is it? Just us?
-Just us.

26:40.960 --> 26:42.280
POLLY: We celebrating?

26:43.800 --> 26:45.200
TOMMY: Just taste this.

27:00.360 --> 27:01.760
What do you think, Arthur?

27:01.840 --> 27:05.400
Yeah, it's good.
Good stuff, really nice.

27:05.480 --> 27:07.400
Too good for the Garrison.

27:07.480 --> 27:10.840
I suppose we could shift it
to the toffs at the Eden Club.

27:11.480 --> 27:13.000
Why? What is it?

27:13.520 --> 27:15.280
That is part of an export drive.

27:16.880 --> 27:19.760
We now have a secure warehouse
in Camden Town

27:19.840 --> 27:22.760
and secure passage to the Poplar Docks.

27:22.840 --> 27:24.680
So, on Monday morning,

27:24.760 --> 27:27.520
we'll be sending out
our first export crates.

27:27.600 --> 27:31.240
A crate of Riley car spares,

27:31.360 --> 27:33.400
bound for Halifax, Nova Scotia.

27:34.240 --> 27:35.800
Where there's prohibition.

27:37.320 --> 27:38.880
Where there is prohibition.

27:40.120 --> 27:42.000
All over Canada and America,

27:42.200 --> 27:45.040
people are making their own booze
in bathtubs.

27:45.160 --> 27:50.360
But rich people in New York,
in Toronto and Boston

27:50.680 --> 27:52.600
are still paying a lot of
money for the real stuff.

27:53.560 --> 27:56.960
So, on Monday,
the first Shelby company crates

27:57.040 --> 28:00.160
will contain a thousand
Riley carburettors.

28:00.840 --> 28:04.840
But hidden in the packing
will be 500 bottles

28:04.920 --> 28:09.120
of the finest quality
single malt Scotch whisky.

28:12.600 --> 28:14.320
And we Shelbys, have a licence

28:14.400 --> 28:16.480
granted by the
Minister Of The Empire himself,

28:17.200 --> 28:19.760
which means our crates
won't be searched.

28:19.840 --> 28:22.800
And, Polly, all of the whisky
will be packed at the docks,

28:22.880 --> 28:26.200
so Michael can do the books
without being involved.

28:26.720 --> 28:29.360
Like I've been telling
you all for a year now,

28:30.160 --> 28:31.760
motor cars are the future.

28:35.880 --> 28:38.600
So, how is your life then, Tom?

28:38.680 --> 28:41.320
On the up, Johnny, on the up.

28:41.400 --> 28:44.880
But, Tom, really, come on, how is it?

28:44.960 --> 28:48.040
You know I hate to
see you not even married yet.

28:48.120 --> 28:51.680
I have a fine looking cousin,
she'll make your life hell.

28:51.760 --> 28:53.000
You deserve her!

28:53.080 --> 28:54.080
(CHUCKLING)

28:55.480 --> 28:58.480
We haven't had a good old
wedding in a long time.

29:01.040 --> 29:02.960
Rather look inside these boxes,
then, Johnny?

29:03.800 --> 29:05.600
What do I want to look
at car parts, Tommy,

29:05.680 --> 29:07.120
when I haven't even got a car?

29:09.960 --> 29:12.040
Faith in family's a fine thing, eh?

29:13.240 --> 29:15.200
And I wouldn't even be counting.

29:16.000 --> 29:18.920
Twenty-five becomes 24, then 24 it is.

29:19.080 --> 29:20.840
Oh, you know I'm no good
with numbers, Tom.

29:22.880 --> 29:25.920
And if 24 ever became 23,

29:27.000 --> 29:28.680
then that'd be tax.

29:29.600 --> 29:31.120
We don't pay tax.

29:31.920 --> 29:33.440
No, Tom.

29:35.200 --> 29:36.720
Good man.

29:46.200 --> 29:48.120
KITCHEN: I put an iron door on,

29:48.200 --> 29:51.080
and we've put iron bars on the
windows and across the skylights.

29:51.160 --> 29:52.480
TOMMY: Good.

29:52.560 --> 29:54.040
So what will you
be keeping in here, Tommy?

29:55.080 --> 29:57.680
Temptation, Billy. Temptation.

30:09.920 --> 30:11.600
(DOOR OPENS)

30:11.680 --> 30:13.760
Morning, Arthur. I was just passing.

30:19.280 --> 30:21.200
ARTHUR: I think I'm in fucking love.

30:22.320 --> 30:23.560
Drink!

30:29.200 --> 30:30.760
She don't know where to look.

30:32.240 --> 30:33.520
Whisky, Tommy?

30:34.640 --> 30:36.400
No, I've got a long drive ahead.

30:36.480 --> 30:37.920
You off home?

30:38.440 --> 30:41.360
Mmm-hmm. Eventually.

30:41.760 --> 30:43.080
To Birmingham.

30:48.720 --> 30:50.000
What's this?

30:52.120 --> 30:53.320
Olives.

30:53.400 --> 30:55.000
Yes, it's miscellaneous.

30:55.920 --> 30:58.240
It's, erm, olives.

30:58.440 --> 31:02.520
Sticks, you know, with little bits
of fucking onion and things.

31:04.680 --> 31:06.000
That's what that is.

31:08.040 --> 31:10.200
We've taken 600 pounds on olives.

31:11.320 --> 31:13.120
Yeah, with little bits of onion.

31:20.960 --> 31:22.440
I told you, Arthur...

31:25.240 --> 31:28.800
The dealers sell the cocaine,
we take a cut.

31:28.880 --> 31:31.000
We don't sell direct.

31:31.440 --> 31:33.080
The Home Secretary's cracking down

31:33.200 --> 31:35.000
and I don't want this,

31:35.080 --> 31:37.680
to fuck up everything else,
you understand?

31:38.880 --> 31:40.920
I understand.

31:41.200 --> 31:43.520
How much of that 600
came out of your pocket?

31:51.400 --> 31:52.880
It's under control.

31:53.240 --> 31:55.760
I put you down here cos people
are scared of you, Arthur.

31:58.360 --> 32:02.000
But if you don't straighten up,
it'll be John's turn in London.

32:03.280 --> 32:05.280
No need.

32:05.360 --> 32:06.680
I can handle it.

32:08.280 --> 32:09.720
It's under control?

32:10.920 --> 32:12.320
It's under control.

32:22.360 --> 32:24.240
Fucking tidy profit, though, eh?

32:28.160 --> 32:29.640
It's happening, Tom.

32:32.720 --> 32:33.920
Good.

32:34.920 --> 32:36.080
Good.

32:41.480 --> 32:43.120
TOMMY: Straighten up, soldier.

32:55.640 --> 32:57.760
Yes, sir, Sergeant Major.

33:26.960 --> 33:28.240
What's your business?

33:29.720 --> 33:32.080
Sorry, I'm, er, I'm lost here.

33:33.640 --> 33:35.000
Yeah, well, you can't stop here.

33:35.120 --> 33:36.880
-Move on.
-All right.

33:38.400 --> 33:40.640
(ENGINE STARTS)

33:46.800 --> 33:48.520
Twenty-three seconds.

33:57.600 --> 34:00.240
It's all right, Ada,
it'll be Andrew for me.

34:04.000 --> 34:05.320
Oh.

34:06.520 --> 34:08.120
I'm looking for Ada.

34:08.200 --> 34:09.560
Who are you?

34:16.920 --> 34:18.680
Ada.

34:18.760 --> 34:20.440
I asked you a question.

34:20.520 --> 34:22.240
It's all right, James.

34:22.320 --> 34:24.560
This is my brother.

34:24.720 --> 34:25.960
Who's he?

34:26.040 --> 34:27.360
He rents a room.

34:27.440 --> 34:29.200
You need to rent out rooms?

34:29.280 --> 34:31.080
Actually, she doesn't charge rent.

34:31.560 --> 34:33.640
He's a writer, which means he's skint.

34:36.560 --> 34:38.120
You get up late these days, Ada.

34:38.200 --> 34:39.920
Mmm. I go to bed late.

34:40.000 --> 34:41.520
TOMMY: Yeah? Where's Karl?

34:42.000 --> 34:43.560
What do you want, Tommy?

34:45.560 --> 34:48.680
Oh, God, before you start
sizing him up for a wedding suit,

34:48.760 --> 34:50.400
he's not interested in me.

34:50.480 --> 34:52.760
-Or in girls of any kind.
-Ada!

34:52.840 --> 34:54.280
What? Tommy won't judge you.

34:54.440 --> 34:56.080
He sure as hell won't go to the police.

34:58.200 --> 35:00.160
Look, I'll go and get dressed.

35:00.240 --> 35:01.920
James...

35:02.000 --> 35:03.680
I'm Thomas.

35:04.320 --> 35:05.440
Pleased to meet you.

35:09.000 --> 35:11.400
Can I have a minute
with my sister, please?

35:13.000 --> 35:14.400
Yes, of course.

35:22.760 --> 35:25.280
So, does your lodger know your name?

35:25.360 --> 35:27.040
Yeah. Thorne.

35:27.480 --> 35:29.400
You think I'd tell anybody
anything else?

35:30.080 --> 35:33.240
Your Brummie boys
are all over the papers.

35:33.320 --> 35:35.440
Just one last push, eh?
Then you'll go legit?

35:35.960 --> 35:39.280
Just one more obstacle to get round,
then it'll all be straight?

35:39.480 --> 35:40.880
Actually, yes.

35:40.960 --> 35:42.120
(GIGGLING)

35:42.320 --> 35:44.480
Personally, I find it quite amusing.

35:44.720 --> 35:47.200
Men like you are becoming
very fashionable down here.

35:47.720 --> 35:50.920
No society party in London
is complete without a gangster

35:51.080 --> 35:52.720
for the girls to go giddy for.

35:54.280 --> 35:56.680
Anyway, what is it that you want?

35:58.720 --> 36:00.600
I don't have any children, Ada,

36:04.560 --> 36:05.880
so I have set up a trust fund.

36:07.440 --> 36:10.680
The beneficiaries
will be John's kids and Karl.

36:12.120 --> 36:15.960
In order for Karl to benefit,
I need your signature.

36:19.040 --> 36:22.440
I've set up an account.

36:22.520 --> 36:26.640
The money will be transferred
in the event of my death.

36:28.640 --> 36:31.000
It'll set them up for a new life.

36:38.400 --> 36:40.000
Are you sick?

36:40.080 --> 36:42.760
I'm just doing
what any ordinary man would,

36:42.840 --> 36:44.320
putting my affairs in order.

37:14.400 --> 37:16.680
DARBY: <i>Did you know they was
going to take the Eden club?</i>

37:16.760 --> 37:19.480
ALFIE: I know about the Eden club, yes.

37:19.560 --> 37:21.600
Did you know they were going
to do it before they did it?

37:21.760 --> 37:24.400
Because that's someone
who's in charge, isn't it?

37:25.080 --> 37:27.080
The one who knows before it happens.

37:27.600 --> 37:29.640
I know what I know, you know.

37:29.720 --> 37:33.920
If you don't know,
then you don't fucking know, do you?

37:34.880 --> 37:37.440
Did you know they was going
to take Wimbledon Docks?

37:38.240 --> 37:40.480
Harringay? The trotting tracks?

37:42.760 --> 37:47.160
Talk, all right?
I genuinely want to hear you.

37:47.240 --> 37:48.560
You've lost control, Alfie.

37:48.640 --> 37:49.960
ALFIE: Have I?

37:50.040 --> 37:51.480
MAN: Everybody knows.

37:54.360 --> 37:56.720
-Talk to me, Alfie.
-Talk to you?

37:58.480 --> 38:01.480
All right, I'll talk to you.
I'll fucking tell you how it was, right?

38:01.560 --> 38:03.520
What happened was this.

38:04.320 --> 38:08.120
All the time you were talking about
dirty fucking Jews.

38:08.200 --> 38:09.440
All the fucking time,

38:09.560 --> 38:11.840
dirty fucking Jews, dirty Kikes,
dirty dustbin lids...

38:11.920 --> 38:13.360
-Everyone makes jokes.
-You want to talk about

38:13.440 --> 38:16.680
-not getting into places?
-Everybody makes fucking jokes.

38:16.760 --> 38:19.120
I didn't know you had
no sense of humour!

38:19.280 --> 38:22.640
And I ain't going
to fucking mention, right,

38:22.720 --> 38:27.040
the great big fuck off elephant
in the room.

38:28.520 --> 38:29.920
Look, Alfie...

38:30.000 --> 38:33.720
How many of my bookies
worked Epsom this last May?

38:33.800 --> 38:35.520
None. None.

38:35.920 --> 38:37.400
Not one.

38:37.480 --> 38:41.320
So, for a few fucking jokes and Epsom,

38:41.400 --> 38:44.880
you fucking invite
a tribe of savages into the city

38:44.960 --> 38:47.920
and just fucking
unlock the fucking gates!

38:52.960 --> 38:55.000
I'm sorry, what are you saying, mate?

38:55.640 --> 38:57.080
I'm saying...

38:58.480 --> 39:00.960
I'm sorry about the Jew thing.

39:02.160 --> 39:04.560
-You saying you're sorry?
-Yeah.

39:05.040 --> 39:07.360
-You're sorry about the Jew thing?
-Yeah.

39:08.080 --> 39:09.840
-Really?
-Yeah.

39:10.640 --> 39:13.440
I want that in writing.
Write that down. He said, "I'm sorry".

39:15.760 --> 39:17.480
And also write down

39:17.800 --> 39:20.320
that all our bookies
can go back to Epsom.

39:20.400 --> 39:22.080
-He didn't say that.
-Who's asking you?

39:22.160 --> 39:23.160
Eh.

39:24.640 --> 39:26.320
Write it down.

39:26.400 --> 39:28.760
It's all right. Come on.

39:28.840 --> 39:30.320
Alfie's an old friend.

39:32.800 --> 39:34.280
My friend.

39:35.680 --> 39:37.240
Now, admit it,

39:38.000 --> 39:41.360
the Peaky Blinders is out of control.

39:41.600 --> 39:43.760
Yeah, they're out
of fucking control, mate.

39:43.840 --> 39:47.160
They come down the canal,
they spread like the fucking clap.

39:48.000 --> 39:49.400
Right. So now they're

39:49.600 --> 39:51.080
-everybody's problem.
-Yeah.

39:51.760 --> 39:53.440
-Alfie.
-Mmm.

39:53.600 --> 39:55.720
You and me, we've been fighting

39:55.800 --> 39:57.480
-since we was at school.
-Yeah.

39:57.640 --> 39:59.760
All right? Now, also,

40:00.040 --> 40:01.880
-we've been friends.
-Mmm, yeah.

40:02.280 --> 40:04.880
You know,
it goes backwards and forwards.

40:06.000 --> 40:07.480
How much better is it
when we're friends?

40:08.120 --> 40:09.560
Oh, it's much better, mate, yeah.

40:09.920 --> 40:11.240
You write that down.

40:11.840 --> 40:12.840
Mmm.

40:13.760 --> 40:15.160
So what we're doing here, right,

40:15.240 --> 40:18.880
is we're writing down some
kind of a deal thing, right?

40:18.960 --> 40:21.560
-Yeah, a written deal.
-Written deal, good.

40:22.040 --> 40:26.840
Well, why don't we discuss
the border between the Italians

40:26.920 --> 40:28.960
and the Jews going back
to Farringdon Road.

40:29.880 --> 40:31.520
-Farringdon Road...
-Yeah, Farringdon Road.

40:31.680 --> 40:33.520
Fuck! That's ancient history.

40:33.800 --> 40:36.440
-Write down Farringdon Road.
-No, no, no, write down Camden Road.

40:36.520 --> 40:38.200
-Farringdon Road.
-Camden Road.

40:38.280 --> 40:39.360
-Write down Farringdon.
-Camden.

40:39.440 --> 40:40.560
-Farringdon.
-Camden.

40:40.640 --> 40:42.400
Write down Camden Road.

40:43.560 --> 40:45.320
Just write down "peace".

40:45.400 --> 40:47.440
Just write down "peace", right,

40:47.640 --> 40:51.840
between the Jews and the Italians.

40:53.240 --> 40:57.120
And war against the gypsies.

41:21.320 --> 41:22.600
Fuck.

41:27.800 --> 41:29.040
(DOOR OPENS)

41:29.120 --> 41:30.880
MAID: Mr Thomas Shelby, madam.

41:44.520 --> 41:45.880
Nice house.

41:50.000 --> 41:51.480
Would you like a whisky?

41:52.040 --> 41:53.600
Scotch or Irish?

41:54.160 --> 41:55.720
Irish.

41:55.800 --> 41:57.480
(GLASSES CLINKING)

42:01.960 --> 42:03.440
Sorry for the short notice.

42:03.560 --> 42:05.600
I was passing.

42:06.880 --> 42:08.640
We're not quite on the Birmingham road.

42:09.160 --> 42:10.880
It was a small diversion.

42:10.960 --> 42:12.480
Sixty miles, I checked.

42:13.520 --> 42:15.480
That's a small diversion these days.

42:17.080 --> 42:19.840
So, I'm a small diversion.

42:19.920 --> 42:21.160
Good.

42:24.040 --> 42:25.800
Your horse is still out on the gallops,

42:25.880 --> 42:27.680
but I had Mickey prepare this report.

42:27.800 --> 42:29.720
You can read it now if you'd like,
then we can go see her.

42:38.720 --> 42:40.920
-(CLEARS THROAT)
-ls there enough light for you to read?

42:41.000 --> 42:42.280
Yes, it's fine.

42:44.880 --> 42:46.320
It's getting quite late.

42:56.120 --> 42:57.120
Mickey says she has
the lungs of an elephant.

42:59.360 --> 43:00.600
She's nimble in the heavy going,

43:00.680 --> 43:01.960
but bounces a little on the hard ground.

43:03.800 --> 43:05.200
Sorry, I'll let you read.

43:08.240 --> 43:10.960
So, he thinks she'll favour
good to soft ground, eh?

43:11.600 --> 43:13.600
-A little juice in the grass.
-Mmm.

43:14.560 --> 43:16.360
Well, that's good for Epsom.

43:18.440 --> 43:21.040
Does he think she's
not good enough for Epsom?

43:22.240 --> 43:23.840
She needs a lot of work.

43:24.680 --> 43:26.320
The race board will need convincing.

43:27.520 --> 43:30.320
-I imagine you have some influence.
-Mmm.

43:32.400 --> 43:34.360
That's the suggested program me
for the next two months.

43:38.440 --> 43:39.800
Your glass is empty.

43:40.280 --> 43:41.760
It's fine.

43:43.920 --> 43:45.560
Are you hungry?

43:46.960 --> 43:48.600
Yes, a bit.

43:49.400 --> 43:50.720
I can prepare something.

43:52.080 --> 43:53.480
Do you have engine oil?

43:56.360 --> 43:59.040
Before I set off for Birmingham,
the car needs oil.

44:01.160 --> 44:02.920
I'm sure my husband
kept some in the garage.

44:03.000 --> 44:04.400
I can get someone to do it.

44:05.400 --> 44:07.240
This evening or tomorrow?

44:11.360 --> 44:14.000
Well, we're so far from anywhere,
people usually stay over.

44:16.520 --> 44:18.440
Especially before cars,
when it was just carriages,

44:18.520 --> 44:20.160
people used to stay over all the time.

44:21.920 --> 44:23.280
But I have a car.

44:25.440 --> 44:26.760
Yes.

44:27.160 --> 44:30.160
And you have engine oil.

44:31.960 --> 44:33.600
Probably.

44:36.000 --> 44:37.680
But it would be very usual.

44:39.960 --> 44:41.400
What would?

44:43.080 --> 44:44.200
For a guest to stay.

44:44.280 --> 44:46.040
We have a whole wing
called the guest wing.

44:46.640 --> 44:48.080
Oh, you...

44:49.680 --> 44:50.960
You have a guest wing.

44:53.040 --> 44:54.560
Well...

45:01.840 --> 45:03.320
May.

45:06.240 --> 45:07.440
(BREATHING UNEVENLY)

45:13.320 --> 45:15.080
Have a smoke.

45:15.160 --> 45:16.800
Thank you.

45:24.960 --> 45:26.880
Ignore this. It's actually all right.

45:30.120 --> 45:32.560
I put all his photos
in a drawer and locked it...

45:34.000 --> 45:35.920
As if that was going
to make a difference.

45:39.520 --> 45:41.600
I'm like a fucking lighthouse keeper...

45:45.720 --> 45:47.360
Out here on my own...

45:49.680 --> 45:51.720
Keeping his flame burning.

45:51.800 --> 45:55.480
But, of course,
when anyone sees a lighthouse

45:56.240 --> 45:57.640
they steer clear, don't they?

46:09.400 --> 46:10.920
Now, do you have a map?

46:14.600 --> 46:16.600
Of the house. Do you have a map?

46:19.120 --> 46:23.200
Because I'm not going to be able
to find my way in the dark.

46:27.600 --> 46:30.480
You see, at midnight,

46:30.560 --> 46:33.400
I'm going to leave my wing

46:34.080 --> 46:35.600
and I'm going to come find you.

46:37.400 --> 46:40.440
And I'm going to turn the handle
of your bedroom door

46:40.520 --> 46:42.480
without making a sound

46:42.560 --> 46:44.280
and none of the maids will know.

46:45.920 --> 46:47.360
You don't know maids.

46:50.040 --> 46:51.400
They hear a pin drop?

46:52.320 --> 46:55.080
If there's a man in the house,
they listen.

46:56.160 --> 46:57.600
They take turns.

46:58.760 --> 47:00.480
So, let them listen.

47:05.640 --> 47:09.360
Right. Day rate, seven shillings.
Loading, unloading.

47:09.520 --> 47:12.200
Night rate, three. Total ten.

47:13.000 --> 47:14.760
Let's go and get a drink.

47:14.920 --> 47:16.240
No, I'm all right.

47:16.400 --> 47:17.920
Come on, it's payday.

47:18.120 --> 47:19.440
Everybody has a drink on payday.

47:19.640 --> 47:21.040
Not me.

47:21.240 --> 47:23.480
You think your mum
don't have a drink on payday?

47:24.360 --> 47:28.320
You think the Lord Almighty
don't have a drink on payday?

47:30.040 --> 47:32.080
Man, it's on fire out there,

47:32.160 --> 47:35.160
women from the BSA offices, honest.

47:35.320 --> 47:38.040
They go out on their own
without their men these days,

47:38.120 --> 47:39.440
in twos and threes now.

47:40.800 --> 47:44.360
Mickey, they go out in twos and
threes and buy their own drinks.

47:49.480 --> 47:53.640
The Marquis,
that's where the BSA secretaries go.

47:57.680 --> 48:02.480
Look, they won't serve a black man
without a Shelby by his side.

48:07.640 --> 48:09.120
So you're using me?

48:12.160 --> 48:13.480
Yeah.

48:13.720 --> 48:15.080
Come on.

48:19.400 --> 48:21.560
(LAUGHTER AND CHATTER)

48:22.760 --> 48:25.600
I told you, I fucking told you,
this city's gone mad.

48:25.920 --> 48:27.560
Girls go out on their own now.

48:30.800 --> 48:32.640
Two pints of dark mild, please.

48:32.840 --> 48:34.640
Fuck that. We're Peaky boys.

48:34.760 --> 48:36.160
Two whiskies.

48:44.440 --> 48:46.520
You get used to it, then you can't stop.

48:50.680 --> 48:52.080
(WHISTLING)

48:53.520 --> 48:55.560
I don't drink with blacks.

48:55.880 --> 48:57.360
Here we fucking go.

48:57.520 --> 48:59.800
Paddy, they're okay.

49:00.400 --> 49:01.520
Not with me, they're not.

49:01.600 --> 49:03.560
I don't drink in pubs with blacks.

49:03.640 --> 49:04.960
So leave.

49:05.800 --> 49:08.400
Look, my dad is the preacher round here.

49:08.600 --> 49:10.400
He has connections, ask anybody.

49:11.520 --> 49:12.720
I couldn't give a fuck who he is.

49:13.480 --> 49:15.040
I'm telling you to leave it, Paddy.

49:15.200 --> 49:17.720
And I'm telling this darkie
to get out of here.

49:17.800 --> 49:19.200
You know something? Fuck off.

49:19.280 --> 49:21.000
It's all right, Isaiah, come on,
leave it.

49:21.080 --> 49:23.360
-We'll go to my cousin's pub.
-I like it here.

49:25.000 --> 49:26.840
You fucking nigger.

49:28.320 --> 49:31.240
(SHOUTING AND SCREAMING)

49:48.760 --> 49:51.280
Paddy! The white kid's a Peaky Blinder!

49:51.440 --> 49:53.080
He's Polly Shelby's son!

49:54.720 --> 49:58.520
He's Polly Shelby's son!
Are you fucking suicidal?

49:58.920 --> 50:00.480
Sir...

50:00.560 --> 50:01.800
Sir, I'm sorry, I didn't know.

50:02.000 --> 50:03.560
Get out!

50:03.720 --> 50:05.080
Get out the fucking pub.

50:05.240 --> 50:06.920
I clearly didn't know.

50:07.120 --> 50:09.240
Fuck, let's go. Let's go!

50:11.480 --> 50:13.320
We ordered some drinks

50:13.600 --> 50:15.360
and we're going to drink them.

50:26.440 --> 50:29.040
His face, man.
Did you see his fucking face?

50:29.120 --> 50:30.880
You punch like a fucking kangaroo.

50:30.960 --> 50:33.920
I seen one once in a circus,
you punch like that.

50:35.160 --> 50:36.960
All right, anyway,
I need a fucking drink.

50:37.040 --> 50:39.760
-It's on you.
-It's on me? You just got paid.

50:39.840 --> 50:41.240
Yeah, from you.

50:41.680 --> 50:44.000
You can get a whisky,
maybe even a dark mild.

50:48.320 --> 50:51.520
Fucking hell,
it's packed in here, isn't it?

50:52.360 --> 50:53.560
JOHN: So it's as easy as that?

50:53.640 --> 50:56.960
Easy as that, John boy.
London, you wouldn't believe it.

50:57.240 --> 50:58.760
Finn, stick your head in a bucket.

50:58.840 --> 51:00.320
No.

51:00.520 --> 51:02.720
The women, John boy, the women...

51:03.280 --> 51:05.720
I've got this one,
she's a dancer, right?

51:05.800 --> 51:07.600
She can do things with her...

51:10.920 --> 51:13.200
If Finn would just piss off,
I'd explain a little bit better.

51:13.480 --> 51:15.760
Well, if it's so good, why are you here?

51:16.640 --> 51:18.440
Decent pints.

51:18.640 --> 51:20.320
The cockneys can't get that right.

51:20.400 --> 51:22.760
He misses us, Finn, that's what it is.

51:24.000 --> 51:27.200
Here they are, look, junior Peaky boys.

51:30.760 --> 51:32.760
What's happened to you?
You been scrapping?

51:34.280 --> 51:35.760
Some idiots at the Marquis of Lorne.

51:35.840 --> 51:38.600
Tried to stop me and Isaiah
from drinking, but it's all right.

51:38.800 --> 51:40.200
We fought them off.

51:40.640 --> 51:42.520
Arthur, we had to stand
our ground and we did.

51:43.760 --> 51:46.200
The Marquis, eh? Where's your dad?

51:47.320 --> 51:49.040
-Preaching.
-Right.

51:52.840 --> 51:54.240
Don't nick any of me chips, Finn!

51:54.320 --> 51:56.280
-Where are you going?
-ARTHUR: We won't be long.

51:58.920 --> 52:00.400
Where are they going?

52:00.480 --> 52:01.720
The Marquis of Lorne.

52:03.040 --> 52:04.400
Shame.

52:04.480 --> 52:06.040
It was a nice pub.

53:59.080 --> 54:00.360
(MOANING)

54:01.800 --> 54:04.440
Eh-up. Bet the big bastard got cut.

54:07.520 --> 54:09.080
You didn't have to do that for me.

54:09.160 --> 54:10.640
We didn't do it for you, Michael.

54:10.720 --> 54:12.880
We did it for the good name
of the company.

54:13.960 --> 54:16.360
None of this happened, all right?

54:16.440 --> 54:18.400
Come on, let's go and get that drink.

54:28.120 --> 54:29.760
(DOOR SLAMS OPEN)

54:29.840 --> 54:31.200
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

54:46.120 --> 54:47.760
CAMPBELL: The date has been set.

54:49.720 --> 54:51.680
Three weeks from today.

54:55.240 --> 54:56.840
You checked out his house?

54:58.640 --> 55:00.360
There's coppers all over it.

55:01.800 --> 55:03.680
You'll take care of them?

55:03.960 --> 55:05.960
No. That would arouse suspicion.

55:07.520 --> 55:09.240
You'll have to deal with them yourself.

55:12.080 --> 55:13.840
And if a copper gets killed?

55:16.160 --> 55:20.040
There will be no consequences
for you, I have given you my word.

55:20.120 --> 55:22.000
Which I know to be worthless.

55:24.040 --> 55:27.960
That is why I have been settling
my affairs in the event of my death.

55:31.560 --> 55:34.440
(CHUCKLING) And making your peace
with God, perhaps?

55:36.760 --> 55:38.480
Well, good luck with that.

55:43.640 --> 55:47.480
I have made arrangements
with men I trust.

55:49.360 --> 55:51.520
If I should die,

55:51.600 --> 55:53.040
then you will die.

55:54.600 --> 55:56.000
Know that.

56:00.840 --> 56:04.280
(FOOTSTEPS RECEDING)

57:29.520 --> 57:31.560
Ritz Hotel. (CLEARS THROAT)

57:31.640 --> 57:33.080
London, Piccadilly.

57:33.160 --> 57:34.920
(PHONE RINGS)

57:42.840 --> 57:44.040
Hello?

57:45.800 --> 57:47.240
<i>Hello?</i>

57:53.440 --> 57:55.080
-Who was that?
-Call got cut.

57:55.640 --> 57:57.920
<i>I guess the telephone lines
in England are not so good, huh?</i>

57:58.000 --> 57:59.000
Hm.

57:59.024 --> 58:04.024
http://hiqve.com/
